 question of whether we need stable assertions around class names and exceptions. There's also the matter of invoking methods and handling exceptions. High-coverage integration testing might actually be advantageous for accessing parameter metadata directly. However, it seems the remaining parts are in toStringImpl, which may not be fully successful.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating method invocation**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using `method.invoke` on `isWrapperFor` with `Integer`. If it doesn't have an interface for `int`, it throws a class issue, which is good to keep in mind. I need to ensure that the method invocation is properly covered, especially if the first unwrap is with `Integer`. In my report, it might be worth counting calls to `Method#invoke`. It seems like I might not need to import `BigDecimal/Types` since we can still assert direct metadata. I should adjust the test name accordingly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_C0sU5UhT2MaOtvsUE9KbKh39|fc_027b4c9c3cbf53050169f17828b46c81a1b6ad01252de6950d", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.hsqldb/hsqldb/2.4.1/src/test/java/org_hsqldb/hsqldb/JDBCParameterMetaDataTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    public void rendersPreparedStatementParameterMethodsInStringRepresentation() throws Exception {\n        try (Connection connection = openConnection()) {\n            try (Statement statement = connection.createStatement()) {\n                statement.execute(\"CREATE TABLE PARAMETER_METADATA_TEST (\"\n                        + \"ID INTEGER, NAME VARCHAR(40), AMOUNT DECIMAL(12, 2))\");\n            }\n\n            try (PreparedStatement statement = connection.prepareStatement(\n                    \"INSERT INTO PARAMETER_METADATA_TEST (ID, NAME, AMOUNT) VALUES (?, ?, ?)\")) {\n                ParameterMetaData parameterMetaData = statement.getParameterMetaData();\n\n                assertThat(parameterMetaData).isInstanceOf(JDBCParameterMetaData.class);\n                assertThat(parameterMetaData.getParameterCount()).isEqualTo(3);\n\n                String rendered = parameterMetaData.toString();\n\n                assertThat(rendered)\n                        .contains(\"parameter_1\")\n                        .contains(\"getParameterClassName=\" + Integer.class.getName())\n                        .contains(\"getParameterType=\" + Types.INTEGER)\n                        .contains(\"getParameterTypeName=INTEGER\")\n                        .contains(\"parameter_2\")\n                        .contains(\"getParameterClassName=\" + String.class.getName())\n                        .contains(\"getParameterType=\" + Types.VARCHAR)\n                        .contains(\"getParameterTypeName=VARCHAR\")\n                        .contains(\"parameter_3\")\n                        .contains(\"getParameterClassName=\" + BigDecimal.class.getName())\n                        .contains(\"getParameterType=\" + Types.DECIMAL)\n                        .contains(\"getParameterTypeName=DECIMAL\")\n                        .contains(\"getPrecision=12\")\n                        .contains(\"getScale=2\")\n                        .doesNotContain(\"toStringImpl_exception\");\n            }\n        }\n    }\n", "newText": "    public void reachesReflectiveStringRenderingForPreparedStatementParameters() throws Exception {\n        try (Connection connection = openConnection()) {\n            try (Statement statement = connection.createStatement()) {\n                statement.execute(\"CREATE TABLE PARAMETER_METADATA_TEST (\"\n                        + \"ID INTEGER, NAME VARCHAR(40), AMOUNT DECIMAL(12, 2))\");\n            }\n\n            try (PreparedStatement statement = connection.prepareStatement(\n                    \"INSERT INTO PARAMETER_METADATA_TEST (ID, NAME, AMOUNT) VALUES (?, ?, ?)\")) {\n                ParameterMetaData parameterMetaData = statement.getParameterMetaData();\n\n                assertThat(parameterMetaData).isInstanceOf(JDBCP